e=Sarah Palin succession and navigation boxes\n|state=collapsed\n|list1=\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=John Stein}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Mayor of [[Wasilla, Alaska|Wasilla]]|years=1996\u20132002}}\n{{s-aft|after=Dianne Keller}}\n\n{{s-bef|before=[[Frank Murkowski]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Governors of Alaska|Governor of Alaska]]|years=2006\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sean Parnell]]}}\n\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Frank Murkowski]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[List of Governors of Alaska|Governor of Alaska]]|years=[[Alaska gubernatorial election, 2006|2006]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sean Parnell]]}}\n\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dick Cheney]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[List of United States Republican Party presidential tickets|nominee]] for [[Vice President of the United States]]|years=[[2008 United States presidential election|2008]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Paul Ryan]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n}}\n\n{{Sarah Palin}}\n{{Governors of Alaska}}\n{{AK Republican gubernatorial nominees}}\n{{Unsuccessful major party VPOTUS candidates}}\n{{USRepVicePresNominees}}\n{{United States presidential election, 2008}}\n{{Alaska Women's Hall of Fame}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Palin, Sarah}}\n[[Category:Sarah Palin|*]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Protestants]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Protestants]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Alaska city council members]]\n[[Category:Alaska Republicans]]\n[[Category:American beauty pageant winners]]\n[[Category:American broadcast news analysts]]\n[[Category:American Christian Zionists]]\n[[Category:American evangelicals]]\n[[Category:American fishers]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American Protestants]]\n[[Category:American television sports announcers]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Christians from Alaska]]\n[[Category:Christians from Arizona]]\n[[Category:Christians from Idaho]]\n[[Category:Climate change denial]]\n[[Category:Female United States vice presidential candidates]]\n[[Category:Former Pentecostals]]\n[[Category:Fox News people]]\n[[Category:Governors of Alaska]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Wasilla, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Palin family|Sarah]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:People from Sandpoint, Idaho]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Scottsdale, Arizona]]\n[[Category:People from the Municipality of Skagway Borough, Alaska]]\n[[Category:People from Wasilla, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Republican Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Republican Party (United States) vice presidential nominees]]\n[[Category:State cabinet secretaries of Alaska]]\n[[Category:Tea Party movement activists]]\n[[Category:2008 United States vice-presidential candidates]]\n[[Category:University of Hawaii at Hilo alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Idaho alumni]]\n[[Category:Women in Alaska politics]]\n[[Category:Women mayors of places in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Women memoirists]]\n[[Category:Women state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Writers from Alaska]]\n[[Category:Writers from Idaho]]\n", "name_user": "Muboshgu", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sarah_Palin"}
{"title_page": "Albania in the Eurovision Song Contest", "text_new": "{{short description|Albania in the Eurovision Song Contest}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox song contest country\n| Name                     = Albania\n| Member station           = [[Radio Televizioni Shqiptar|RTSH]] \n| National selection event = \n{{Collapsible list\n | title                   = National final\n | '''[[Festivali i K\u00ebng\u00ebs]]'''\n | 2004\u20132020\n}}\n| ESC apps                 = 16 (9 finals)\n| ESC first                = [[Eurovision Song Contest 2004|2004]]\n| ESC best                 = 5th: [[Eurovision Song Contest 2012|2012]]\n| ESC worst                = 17th <small>SF</small>: [[Eurovision Song Contest 2007|2007]]\n| Website                  = <!-- Square brackets (\"[\" and \"]\") needed for external link here -->\n| EBU page                 = https://eurovision.tv/country/albania\n| Current                  = 2020\n}}\n\n[[Albania]] has participated in the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] 16 times since its debut in {{escyr|2004}}, and has placed in the top ten two times. [[Festivali i K\u00ebng\u00ebs]], a long-standing song contest that takes place every year in Albania since 1962, is used to select the country's entrant for that year's Eurovision Song Contest. \n\nIn 2004, Albania's first entry at Eurovision, [[Anjeza Shahini]], finished seventh in the final. This remained the country's best result in the contest until {{escyr|2012}}, when [[Rona Nishliu]] placed fifth.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== 2000s ===\n\nThe national broadcaster of Albania, [[Radio Televizioni Shqiptar]] (RTSH), made the country's debut at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2004|2004 contest]] in [[Istanbul]] with the song \"[[The Image of You]]\" performed by [[Anjeza Shahini]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The end of a decade: Istanbul 2004 |url=https://eurovision.tv/story/the-end-of-a-decade-istanbul-2004 |website=[[eurovision.tv]] |accessdate=2 April 2020 |language=English |date=25 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Bakker |first1=Sietse |title=No new countries at next Eurovision Song Contest |url=http://esctoday.com/747 |website=esctoday.com |accessdate=2 April 2020 |language=English |date=27 November 2002}}</ref> The country received 106 points in the grand final and finished in the seventh place remaining the country's highest placement until 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eurovision Song Contest\u2013Countries: Albania |url=https://eurovision.tv/country/albania |website=[[eurovision.tv]] |accessdate=2 April 2020 |language=English}}</ref> In 2005, due to the country's top 11 placement the previous year, the succeeding entry \"[[Tomorrow I Go]]\" by [[Ledina \u00c7elo]] automatically qualified for the grand final and reached the sixteenth place in [[Kyiv]]. The following year, [[Luiz Ejlli]] and his entry \"[[Zjarr e ftoht\u00eb]]\" failed to qualify for the grand final in [[Athens]] simultaneously marking the first time in their participation history.\n\nThe 2007 entry was [[Frederik Ndoci]] with \"[[Hear My Plea]]\", performed at [[Festivali I K\u00ebng\u00ebs 45]] as \"Balada e gurit\" (The stone ballad). The song was performed at Eurovision in both English and Albanian. In the semi-final of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2007|2007 contest]] he received 49 points, placing 17th of 28 in his semi-final and failing to qualify for the final.\n\nThe winner of [[Festivali I K\u00ebng\u00ebs 46]] was \"[[Zemr\u00ebn e lam\u00eb peng]]\" (Hearts trapped in time) by [[Olta Boka]]. However the result of the juries that selected the winner was controversial and rumours arose that the final two judges intentionally awarded high marks to Boka in order to avoid sending the runners-up, Flaka Krelani and Doruntina Disha, to the contest. Press reactions in Albania were not happy with the decision, and RTSH announced that they would investigate into alleged cheating by the final two judges to award their points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esctoday.com/9917|title=Albania: press reaction on Festivali i K\u00ebng\u00ebs|last=Klier|first=Marcus|date=2007-12-17|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=2008-11-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esctoday.com/9930|title=Albania: Festivali I Kenges result under investigation|last=Viniker|first=Barry|date=2007-12-19|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=2008-11-03}}</ref> Despite this, Olta Boka's victory remained, and she sang for Albania at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2008]] in [[Belgrade]], [[Serbia]]. She qualified for the final, coming 9th in a field of 19 in the second semi-final, and in the final she received 55 points, coming equal 17th in a field of 25.\n\nAlbania was the first country to select both their artist and publicly present their song for Eurovision 2009. The winner was again selected by Festivali I K\u00ebng\u00ebs. The winner of [[Festivali I K\u00ebng\u00ebs 47]] was [[Kejsi Tola]] with the song \"[[M\u00eb merr n\u00eb \u00ebnd\u00ebrr]]\" (Take me in your dreams), which was composed by the composers of Albania's first entry Edmond Zhulali and Agim Do\u00e7i.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esctoday.com/12771|title=Albania decided: Kejsi Tola to Eurovision!|last=Klier|first=Marcus|date=2008-12-21|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=2008-12-21}}</ref> The song was performed in English as \"[[Carry Me in Your Dreams]]\".<ref name=\"English\">{{cite web|url=http://www.esctoday.com/13466|title=Albania: Kejsi Tola to sing Carry me in your dreams|last=Hondal|first=Victor|date=2009-03-08|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=2009-03-08}}</ref> Albania finished 7th out of 19 in the 2nd semifinal with 73 points, thus qualifying for the final. In the final, where both jury and televoting were used, Albania scored 48 points, finishing 17th in a field of 25. However, had only televoting been used Albania would have placed 11th in the contest. Conversely if only jury voting had been used Albania would have placed 23rd.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/news?id=3503&_t=Exclusive%3A+Split+jury%2Ftelevoting+results+out%21|title=Exclusive: Split jury/televoting results out!|last=Bakker |first=Sietse|date=2009-07-31|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=2009-08-06}}</ref>\n\n=== 2010s ===\n\nThe winner of [[Festivali I K\u00ebng\u00ebs 48]] was decided on 27 December, with [[Juliana Pasha]] winning over former winner [[Anjeza Shahini]]. She represented Albania at Eurovision 2010 in Oslo with the song \"It's All about You\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esctoday.com/14714|title=Albania sends Juliana Pasha to Eurovision|last=Klier|first=Marcus|date=2009-12-27|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=27 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/news?id=7833&_t=Juliana+Pasha+to+represent+Albania+in+Oslo!|title=Juliana Pasha to represent Albania in Oslo!|last=Brey|first=Marco|date=2009-12-27|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=27 December 2009}}</ref> The song was a typical up-tempo composition, and has been compared to [[Christina Aguilera]]'s \"[[Keeps Gettin' Better]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tmiRcVSON2E|title=Juliana Pasha's song compared to \"Keeps Gettin Better\"|date=2009-12-29|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=2009-12-29}}</ref> and [[Britney Spears]]' \"[[Womanizer (song)|Womanizer]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G47yPRmFdOc|title=Juliana Pasha's song compared to \"Womanizer\"|date=2009-12-25|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=2009-12-25}}</ref> Albania came 6th in the first semi-final with 76 points, thus qualifying for the final. In the final, Juliana finished 16th with 62 points which included 12 points from Macedonia.\n\nThe Albanian participant for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2011|2011 Eurovision Song Contest]] was chosen in [[Albania in the Eurovision Song Contest 2011|Festivali i K\u00ebng\u00ebs 49]] in December 2010. The winner of 2011's Festival of Song was [[Aurela Ga\u00e7e]], winning for the third time after 10 years. Her song was named \"''K\u00ebnga ime''\" (\"My Song\") and it was translated into [[English language|English]] with the name \"[[Feel the Passion]]\", published in 12 March 2011, during a show called \"''Historia nis k\u00ebtu''\" (\"The story begins here\") in [[RTSH]]. Albania participated in Semi-Final 1 against 18 other countries, fighting for a place in the grand final in 14 May. However they missed out on qualification for the final for the first time in 4 years, coming 14th.\n\nAlbania competed in the 2012 competition with the song \"Suus\", which was performed by Rona Nishliu. The song got through to the final, coming in 5th place overall with 146 points. Rona Nishliu from Kosovo achieved a record result for Albania.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/history/by-year/contest?event=1593#Scoreboard | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130122082700/http://www.eurovision.tv/page/history/by-year/contest?event=1593 |archivedate=2013-01-22 | title=Eurovision Song Contest 2012 Grand Final | publisher=Eurovision Song Contest | accessdate=2 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\nAlbania competed in the 2013 Eurovision Song Contest with the song \"[[Identitet]]\" which was performed by [[Adrian Lulgjuraj]] and [[Bledar Sejko]]. This song was chosen as the winner through the [[Festivali i K\u00ebng\u00ebs]]. The results depended on the jury voting only. Among the experts in the jury was the Italian Head of Delegation at the Eurovision Song Contest, [[Nicola Caligiore]], who greeted and gave the points in [[English language|English]] for all the viewers from the Eurovision.tv webcast.<ref>http://www.eurovision.tv/page/news?id=adrian_lulgjuraj_and_bledar_sejko_win_festivali_i_kenges</ref>\nAlbania came 14th in the second semi-final of the 2013 [[Eurovision Song Contest]] in [[Malm\u00f6]] and did not make it into the grand final.\n\nOn 28 December 2013, [[Herciana Matmuja]] won [[Festivali i K\u00ebng\u00ebs 52]] (the 52nd national final of Albania) and was therefore chosen to represent Albania in [[Eurovision 2014]] with her song '[[Zem\u00ebrimi i nj\u00eb nate]]'.<ref>{{cite news|title=Albania: Herciana Matmuja wins Wins Festivali i K\u00ebng\u00ebs 52 with Zem\u00ebrimi i nj\u00eb nate|url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2013/12/28/albania-herciana-matmuja-festivali-i-kenges-52/35988/|accessdate=23 March 2014|newspaper=wiwibloggs.com|date=28 December 2014}}</ref> In the time before Eurovision 2014 she recorded both English and Albanian versions of this song.<ref>{{cite news|title=Albania: Hersiana Matmuja records ESC song in two languages.|url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2014/02/12/albania-hersiana-records-song-two-languages/39335/|accessdate=23 March 2014|newspaper=wiwibloggs.com|date=12 February 2014}}</ref> On 16 March she released the final version of '[[Zem\u00ebrimi i nj\u00eb nate|One Night's anger]]' for Eurovision 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=ALBANIA: HERSIANA MATMUJA REVEALS ONE NIGHT's ANGER|url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2014/03/16/albania-hersiana-matmuja-reveals-one-nights-anger/43096/|accessdate=23 March 2014|newspaper=wiwibloggs.com|date=16 March 2014}}</ref> Albania failed to qualify for the second year in a row.\n\nOn 28 December 2014, [[Elhaida Dani]] won [[Festivali i K\u00ebng\u00ebs 53]] with the song \"[[Diell]]\", and this represented Albania at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2015]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eurovoix.com/2014/12/28/albania-elhaida-dani-is-off-to-vienna/|title=Albania: Elhaida Dani Is Off To Vienna|work=Eurovoix.com|last=Granger|first=Anthony|date=28 December 2014|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref> On 23 February 2015 it was announced that the songwriters had decided to withdraw the song and Dani would perform something else at Eurovision.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eurovoix.com/2015/02/23/albania-diell-withdrawn/|title=Albania: \"Diell\" Withdrawn|work=Eurovoix.com|last=Taylor|first=Richard|date=23 February 2015|accessdate=23 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224052047/http://eurovoix.com/2015/02/23/albania-diell-withdrawn/|archive-date=24 February 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The following day it was revealed that Dani would perform \"[[I'm Alive (Elhaida Dani song)|I'm Alive]]\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Granger|first1=Anthony|title=Albania: Elhaida To Sing \"I\u2019m Alive\"|url=http://eurovoix.com/2015/02/24/albania-elhaida-to-sing-im-alive/|publisher=eurovoix|date=24 February 2015|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 December 2015 [[Eneda Tarifa]] won Festivali i K\u00ebng\u00ebs 54 with her song \"[[P\u00ebrrall\u00eb]]\" which meant she would represent Albania in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2016]]. Albania was the first country to reveal both the artist and song together. It was later translated into English and called \"Fairytale\", and the music video premiered on the evening news on TVSH. Albania failed to qualify, coming only 16th out of 18 in the second semi-final.\n\nAfter failing to qualify once again in 2017 with [[Lindita (singer)|Lindita]] and the song \"[[World (Lindita song)|World]]\", Albania returned to the grand final in 2018 with the song \"[[Mall (song)|Mall]]\" by [[Eugent Bushpepa]]. It finished 11th of 26 in the final receiving 184 points, giving Albania its third best result in the contest since their debut. The song fared better with the juries, coming 7th in the final respectively.\n\nIn 2019, Albania selected [[Jonida Maliqi]] to represent them with the song \"[[Ktheju tok\u00ebs]]\". Albania succeeded in qualifying from the second semi-final, making it the first time Albania had qualified twice in a row since 2009 and 2010.\n\n== Contestants ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|+Table key\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#CCC\"|{{center|2}}\n|Second place\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#A4EAA9\"|{{center|'''X'''}}\n|Entry selected but did not compete \n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Artist\n! Language\n! Title\n! Final\n! Points\n! Semi\n! 